# ── Secrets ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# A real config holds your WireGuard private_key + preshared_key and your real
# endpoint. NEVER commit it. Commit config.example.json instead. Match config.json
# anywhere (daemon/, install/, …) — only the .example is tracked.
config.json

# ── Rust build artifacts ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Matches target/, ui/src-tauri/target/, and any other `target/` dir.
target/

# ── JS / frontend ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
node_modules/
dist/
dist-ssr/
*.local

# ── Tauri generated ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
gen/schemas/

# ── Logs ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
*.log
npm-debug.log*
pnpm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*

# ── OS / editor cruft ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
.DS_Store
*.swp
*.swo
.idea/
.vscode/*
!.vscode/extensions.json

# NOTE: Cargo.lock IS committed on purpose — wirefinder ships binaries
# (daemon, cli, ui), so a locked, reproducible dependency set is what CI and
# releases build against. Do not ignore it.
